Metric Definition

The three metrics I have chosen to compare the segregation in the cities are the dissimilarity index, the Gini coefficient, and the interaction index.

The dissimilarity index ranges from 0.0 to 1.0 (with 0.0 meaning complete integration and 1.0 meaning complete segregation) and measures the percentage of a groups population that would have to change residence for each neighborhood to have the same percentage of that group as the metropolitan area overall. The index is a measure of evenness, and in the equation you can see that it compares each census tracts minority population against the whole citys minority population.

The dissimilarity index is calculated by the following formula:

\[\sum_{i=1}^n\frac{[t_i|(p_i-P)|]}{[2TP(1-P)]}\]

where the variables are defined below:
\(\sf{t_{i}}\) = total population of i
P = ratio of X to T (proportion of the metropolitan areas population that is minority)
\(\sf{p_{i}}\) = ratio of \(\sf{x_{i}}\) to \(\sf{t_{i}}\) (proportion of area is population that is minority)
T = sum of all \(\sf{t_{i}}\) (total population)
X = sum of all \(\sf{x_{i}}\) (total minority population)

The Gini coefficient ranges from 0.0 to 1.0 (with 0.0 meaning complete integration and 1.0 meaning complete segregation) and measures the mean absolute difference between all minority proportions weighted across all areal units. In the equation, every single areal unit is compared against every other areal unit to give a maximum weighted mean difference. The Gini coefficient is also a measure of evenness.

The Gini coefficient is calculated by the following formula:

\[\frac{\sum_{i=1}^n \sum_{j=1}^n t_it_j|(p_i-p_j)|}{2T^2P(1-P)}\] where the variables are defined below: \(\sf{t_{i}}\) = total population of i
\(\sf{t_{j}}\) = total population of j \(\sf{p_{i}}\) = ratio of \(\sf{x_{i}}\) to \(\sf{t_{i}}\) (proportion of area is population that is minority)
\(\sf{p_{j}}\) = ratio of \(\sf{x_{j}}\) to \(\sf{t_{j}}\) (proportion of area js population that is minority)
T = sum of all \(\sf{t_{i}}\) (total population)
P = ratio of X to T (proportion of the metropolitan areas population that is minority)

The interaction index ranges from 0.0 to 1.0 (the lower the value, the higher the segregation and vice versa) measures the exposure of minority group members to members of the majority group as the minority-weighted average of the majority proportion of the population in each areal unit. In the interaction index formula, the equation takes into account each tracts minority population proportion, as well as each tracts majority population proportion. The interaction index is different from the above two formulas as it instead is a measure of exposure instead of a measure of evenness.

The interaction index is calculated by the following formula:

\[\sum_{i=1}^n[(\frac{x_i}{X})(\frac{y_i}{t_i})]\] where the variables are defined below: \(\sf{x_{i}}\) = the minority population of area i
X = sum of all \(\sf{x_{i}}\) (total minority population)
\(\sf{y_{i}}\) = the majority population of area i
\(\sf{t_{i}}\) = total population of i

Given a small data set containing census tracts of 14 cities, I used the above formulas to calculate their dissimilarity, Gini, and interaction coefficients. The final results are displayed below.

## 14  milwaukee     0.6187397

If we remember, a value of 0.0 means complete integration while a value of 1.0 means complete segregation. Right off the bat, we can see immediately that there are not any extreme outliers. All of the data fits within a range of (0.3217329, 0.6187397), with Oklahoma City being the city of most integrated, while Milwaukee takes the title of most segregated.

Next, we have the Gini coefficient graph:

We can see that again, Oklahoma City also has the lowest Gini coefficient, meaning it is also the best integrated city in our dataset. However, it is actually Baltimore that has the highest Gini coefficient, with St.Louis coming in 2nd highest and Milwaukee taking a close 3rd. But when you compare the Gini graph with the dissimilarity graph, you can notice that nearly all the cities stay relatively the same - which makes sense, given that these two coefficients measure the evenness of the city. The similarities between these two graphs tell us that these two different formulas are consistent in their results.

Now this graph should definitely look different because a lower value indicates higher levels of segregation while a higher value indicates higher levels of integration, which is the complete opposite of the first two equations. We can see that Baltimore again scores the highest in segregation - with a low of 0.2170937 - while we have a newcomer to enter the scoreboard: Denver with a high index of 0.6852802. Remember that the interaction index is a measure of exposure - the exposure of a minority group member to members of the majority group.

Metric Proposal

My metric proposal is a simple equation:

\[\sum_{i=1}^n \frac{x_i}{T}\] where the variables are defined below:
\(\sf{x_{i}}\) = the minority population at area i
T = sum of all \(\sf{t_{i}}\) (total population)

The Brian coefficient is very simple: take the summative value of each ratio of minority populations over the total population of the whole metropolitan for each areal unit. It takes into account of only minorities in whole city. It is simple and effective, and values range from 0.0 to 1.0, with a higher number meaning higher amounts of segregation.

Below are the results for the Brian coefficient:

##          city my.metric
## 1    syracuse 0.1380149
## 2  pittsburgh 0.1455801
## 3      dayton 0.1977738
## 4          kc 0.2057428
## 5     memphis 0.2085507
## 6      denver 0.2107780
## 7     wichita 0.2114579
## 8    st_louis 0.2406595
## 9   milwaukee 0.2652331
## 10    ok_city 0.2829450
## 11   columbus 0.2853474
## 12 charleston 0.3277545
## 13    chicago 0.4591945
## 14  baltimore 0.6117491

As you can see, the coefficients results are not very similar to the other metrics. It is very poor and does not actually give a good measure of segregation. I would strongly advise not to use this formula as it is very weak in accurately measuring segregation in a city.
